# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: absinthe
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:absinthe/0-0-1-3] One drink per hour is approximately the amount the body can metabolize.
[src:absinthe/0-0-1-3] Three drinks per night was selected as a target below the amounts recognized by NIAAA as binge drinking (4 drinks for women, 5 drinks per men).
[src:absinthe/0-0-1-3] In both national research and at FE Warren rates of injuries, assaults, criminal behavior and other problems increase dramatically with binge drinking.
[src:absinthe/0-0-1-3] The first tier included screening of all personnel for binge drinking utilizing a measure such as the Alcohol Use Disorders Identification Test (AUDIT).
[src:absinthe/0-0-1-3] Persons identified as possibly at risk were offered an alcohol screening consultation with the Alcohol and Drug Abuse Prevention and Treatment (ADAPT) program.
[src:absinthe/0-0-1-3] Consistent with Air Force policy all active duty members who had alcohol-related misconduct incidents were also referred for evaluation.
[src:absinthe/0-0-1-3] Based on evaluation results individuals were provided educational and motivational enhancement interventions, or if found to have a substance use disorder, entered into a treatment program.
[src:absinthe/0-0-1-3] This included development of the name 0-0-1-3 as both a slogan and a guideline for low risk alcohol use.
[src:absinthe/0-0-1-3] Personnel from the age range at highest risk for binge drinking, 18-25, were involved in development and execution of these actions.
[src:absinthe/0-0-1-3] Metrics collected in 2005 showed a "74% decrease in alcohol-related incidents such as driving violations, public drunkenness, domestic violence, sexual assault, thefts, and other infractions.
[src:absinthe/0-0-1-3] The base also reported 81% fewer cases of underage drinking and 45% fewer drunken-driving arrests." Multiple other military bases adopted elements of the program including a grant-funded trials at five bases.
[src:absinthe/0-0-1-3] The program served as the model for the Air Force's Culture of Responsible Choices (CoRC) program.
[src:absinthe/0-0-1-3] A **0-0-1-3** program was also implemented by the senior administration of the United States Naval Academy in response to a string of alcohol-related incidents that generated a large amount of negative publicity during the 2005-2006 school year.
[src:absinthe/0-0-1-3] Its primary aim there is to "promote responsible alcohol use" within the brigade of midshipmen.
[src:absinthe/0-0-1-3] While the senior leadership at the Naval Academy insists that 0-0-1-3 is only a guideline for responsible alcohol use, its enforcement involves mandatory, random breathalyzer tests for all midshipmen regardless of age or rank.
[src:absinthe/0-0-1-3] Those found in "violation" of 0-0-1-3 (evidenced by having a BAC above 0.08) are placed on record as having alcohol abuse issues, and repeat offenders are subject to severe administrative infractions, up to and including expulsion.
[src:absinthe/0-0-1-3] Military Academy (West Point) nor the U.S.
[src:absinthe/0-0-1-3] Air Force Academy conducts random breathalyzers or punishes students simply for blowing above a particular BAC when not driving a motor vehicle.
[src:absinthe/absente] Prior to 2009, Absente sold in the U.S. contained no grande wormwood (*Artemisia absinthium*), the essential herb from which absinthe derives its name.
[src:absinthe/absente] The maker substituted southernwood (*Artemisia abrotanum*) and the product was bottled with sugar, two critical aspects that differentiated Absente as an anise liqueur and not an absinthe by any traditional reference.
[src:absinthe/absente] The ingredients of Absente are listed in order as alcohol, sugar, a combination of "essences", infusions and distillates, and two artificial dyes, FD&C Yellow #5 and Blue #1.
[src:absinthe/absente] Following the re-legalization of genuine absinthe in the U.S. in 2007, the North American importer introduced a reformulated version that includes grande wormwood (April, 2009) in an apparent effort to improve its consumer appeal.
[src:absinthe/absente] The new label proclaims, "Now With Wormwood!".
[src:absinthe/absente] The version marketed in Europe under the same name is and has always been made with "essence of grande wormwood" (*Artemisia absinthium*).
[src:absinthe/absente] The label design differs mildly from the U.S. version by having "Liqueur aux Plantes d'Absinthe" above the main label and a silver capsule.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] Wormwood's relative mugwort was traditionally used as a remedy for a variety of complaints, especially those of a gynaecological nature, and so the wormwood genus bears the name of the Greek goddess of childbirth, Artemis.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] The specific name derives from *apsínthion*, the Greek term for the plant.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] "Wormwood" itself is an alteration of Old English *wermod*, which is of obscure origin.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] The German cognate *Wermut* is the source of the term vermouth, used in French and English to describe a kind of wine traditionally flavoured with wormwood.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] Leaves are spirally arranged, greenish-grey colored above, white below, covered with silky silvery-white trichomes, and bearing minute oil-producing glands.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] The basal leaves are up to 250 mm (10 in) long, bi- to tripinnate with long petioles, with the cauline leaves (those on the stem) smaller, 50–100 mm (2–4 in) long, less divided, and with short petioles.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] The uppermost leaves can be both simple and sessile (without a petiole).
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] Flowers are pale yellow, tubular, and clustered in spherical bent-down heads (capitula), which are in turn clustered in leafy and branched panicles.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] Flowering occurs from early summer to early autumn; pollination is anemophilous.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] The plant can easily be cultivated in dry soil.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] It should be planted under bright exposure in fertile, midweight soil.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] It prefers soil rich in nitrogen, and can be propagated by ripened cuttings taken in spring or autumn in temperate climates, or by seeds in nursery beds.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] Growing the plant with others tends to stunt their growth; accordingly, it is not considered to be a good companion plant.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] *A. absinthium* also self-seeds generously.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] It is naturalised in some areas away from its native range, including much of North America and the Kashmir Valley of India.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] This plant, and its cultivars "Lambrook Mist" and "Lambrook Silver" have gained the Royal Horticultural Society's Award of Garden Merit.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] These two short cultivars are very similar and more silver than typical British absinthium material and probably derive from southern Europe.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] "Lambrook Silver" is the earliest of these cultivars, having been selected in the late 1950s by Margery Fish, who developed the garden at East Lambrook Manor.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] "Lambrook Mist" was selected about 30 years later by Andrew Norton, a subsequent owner of the garden.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] Both gained their Awards of Garden Merit during the RHS Artemisia Trial 1991–3.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] Cultivar "Silver Ghost" is a taller, silver plant, which flowers much later (August–September) than typical absinthium (June–July) in Britain, and so holds its silver appearance for longer.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] This and a more feathery-leaved cultivar "Persian Lace" were selected by National Collection Holder John Twibell in the 1990s.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] Wormwood herb contains bitter substances from the group of sesquiterpene lactones; absinthin, at 0.20 to 0.28%, is the main component of these bitter substances.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] Essential oils make up 0.2 to 0.8% and contain (-) - thujone, (+) - isothujone, thujyl alcohol and its esters, chamazulene and other mono- and sesquiterpenes.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] In Bailen et al 2013 and Gonzalez-Coloma et al 2013 the Gonzalez-Coloma group discovered a chemotype that does not produce β-thujone but does contain terpenoids not seen elsewhere.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] It is an ingredient in the spirit absinthe, and is used for flavouring in some other spirits and wines, including bitters, bäsk, vermouth, and pelinkovac.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] As a folk medicine, it is claimed to counteract poor appetite and to treat various diseases such as Crohn's disease and IgA nephropathy.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] Wormwood was traditionally relatively common as a bittering spice in farmhouse brewing in Denmark, and to some extent Estonia.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] In 18th-century England, wormwood was sometimes used instead of hops in beer.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] According to Nicholas Culpeper, a stinking breath can be cured by "drinking a glass of Wormwood beer every morning".
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] Historical sources describe the use of *Artemisia absinthium* as an anthelmintic and antiprotozoal remedy, with modern studies reporting antibacterial, antifungal, and antibiofilm activity of its extracts.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] Wormwood-based alcoholic preparations, including absinthe, were also prescribed as prophylaxis during the 19th-century French conquest of Algeria.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] Wormwood clippings and cuttings are added to chicken nesting boxes to repel lice, mites, and fleas.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] Bailen *et al.* 2013 and Gonzalez-Coloma *et al.* 2013 find the unique terpenoids of the Gonzalez-Coloma chemotype make this strain especially promising for insect control.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] As of 2020 a company named EcoflorAgro is investing heavily into increasing the planted area of this strain, hoping to commercialize it to a degree attempted – but never achieved due to unreliable supply – for other botanical insecticides before.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] Most chemotypes of *A. absinthium* contain (−)-α- and/or (+)-β-thujone, though some do not.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] (−)-α-Thujone by itself is a GABAA receptor antagonist that can cause convulsions when administered in large amounts to animals and humans.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] However, there is only one case of documented toxicity of wormwood, in which a 31-year-old man drank 10 mL of steam-distilled pure volatile oil of wormwood, wrongly believing it was absinthe liqueur.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] Medicinal extracts of wormwood have not been shown to cause seizures or other adverse effects at usual doses.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] Thujones have not been shown to be the cause of excessive doses' toxicity for any kind of wormwood extracts, including absinthe.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] In the apocalyptic Book of Revelation ending the Bible, the star named "Wormwood" falls to earth and turns a third of its waters bitter.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] Similarly where the Biblical Hebrew word לענה (*la'anah*) appears in the Hebrew Bible, it is generally translated into English as "wormwood".
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] The word occurs nine times in the Hebrew Bible, seven times with the implication of bitterness and twice as a proper noun, in the Greek translation *apsinthos*, naming the physical meteor in its orbit, in Revelation 8:11.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] The English rendering "wormwood" additionally refers to the dark green oil produced by the plant, which was used to kill intestinal worms.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] The Ukrainian city Chernobyl, notable for its catastrophic nuclear disaster in 1986, is named from one of the Ukrainian names for common wormwood: чорнобиль, *chornóbyl'* (or more commonly полин звичайний *polýn zvycháynyy*, 'common artemisia').
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] The name is inherited from Proto-Slavic *čьrnobylъ or *čьrnobyl, a compound of *čьrnъ, 'black' + *bylь, 'grass', the parts related to Ukrainian: чорний, romanized: *chórnyy*, lit.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] 'black' and било *byló*, 'stalk', which may also refer to *A. vulgaris*.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] Lucretius, reflecting on life in the Roman Republic before 50 BCE, stated in his poem De rerum natura that, "Physicians, when they wish to treat children with a nasty dose of wormwood, first smear the rim of the cup with a sweet coat of yellow honey.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] The children, too young as yet for foresight, are lured by the sweetness at their lips into swallowing the bitter draught.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] Nicholas Culpeper insisted that wormwood was the key to understanding his 1651 book *The English Physitian*.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] Richard Mabey describes Culpeper's entry on this bitter-tasting plant as "stream-of-consciousness" and "unlike anything else in the herbal", and states that it reads "like the ramblings of a drunk".
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] Culpeper biographer Benjamin Woolley suggests the piece may be an allegory about bitterness, as Culpeper had spent his life fighting the Establishment, and had been imprisoned and seriously wounded in battle as a result.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] William Shakespeare referred to wormwood in *Romeo and Juliet*: Act 1, Scene 3.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] Juliet's childhood nurse said, "For I had then laid wormwood to my dug" meaning that the nurse had weaned Juliet, then aged three, by using the bitter taste of wormwood on her nipple.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] He also referred to wormwood in *Hamlet*: Act 3, Scene 2.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] Hamlet said, "That's wormwood" in response to the Player Queen expressing distaste for remarriage.
[src:absinthe/absinth-wormwood] Edwin Arlington Robinson relates in a poem how Cliff Klingenhagen gave a guest a glass of wine while drinking a glass of wormwood himself.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-fountain] A perforated or slotted spoon, sometimes with a trough, is used to dissolve a sugar cube while slowly adding the ice-cold water to a glass of absinthe.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-fountain] Sugar is used optionally to sweeten the drink and counteract its mild bitterness (prior to the introduction of the spoon, the drink was sweetened with either a simple or gum syrup).
[src:absinthe/absinthe-fountain] The spoon is normally flat, with a notch in the handle where it rests on the rim of the glass.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-fountain] Originating in the mid-1870s (when the mass production of sugar cubes started), their use increased over the 1880s and 1890s and were often stamped with brand names or logos as advertising, much like modern alcohol paraphernalia.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-fountain] Sometimes they were sold as tourist items; for example, some might be shaped like the Eiffel Tower, such as the spoon Eiffel Tower #7, which was made for the inauguration of the building in 1889.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-fountain] Most of the hundreds of designs were quite utilitarian and inexpensive; nonetheless, the vintage spoons currently are collectibles.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-fountain] A less common variation of the absinthe spoon is similar to iced tea spoons.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-fountain] By contrast, these have a normal spoon bowl and the sugar holder built into the handle.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-fountain] Another sugar tool, the grille, lacks the overall spoon shape.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-fountain] Rather, it is generally a perforated metal shallow dish with three or more prongs that hold it above the glass.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-fountain] The grille is used in the same way as the spoon.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-fountain] Adding ice cold water to absinthe is the usual method of preparation, as absinthe is most commonly bottled at high proof with the expectation of being diluted to approximately the strength of wine.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-fountain] The addition of water also causes a clouding, called the *louche* (called ouzo effect in other drinks).
[src:absinthe/absinthe-fountain] A water carafe is the original, and the most basic, way to add water.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-fountain] As with other items, many have been found with brand names on them.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-fountain] The carafe is held above the glass and water is delicately added in a thin stream.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-fountain] Fountains, ornamental ice-water drip dispensers, appeared in bars and bistros in the late 1800s as absinthe gained greater popularity.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-fountain] The goal was to improve efficiency of the bartender that now was able use the fountain to make multiple drinks simultaneously.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-fountain] The absinthe fountain can also be brought directly to the table, where the patrons use it to properly prepare their absinthe drinks together, without the need for the steady hand required by a carafe.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-fountain] Most often the fountain design includes a large glass globe with multiple (2–6) spigots filled with ice and water on a tall metal stand.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-fountain] Swiss fountains are occasionally made of pottery with a lot of spigots.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-fountain] In some instances a device called a brouilleur was employed.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-fountain] A brouilleur is a glass or metal bowl which sits on the absinthe glass and acts like a personal absinthe fountain.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-fountain] Ice and water are added to the bowl, which has a small hole at the bottom, allowing the ice-cold water to slowly drip through.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-fountain] Sugar, if preferred, can be added directly to the bowl, or in some cases to a built-in grille.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-fountain] Absinthe was originally served in normal bar-ware, but eventually specialised glasses became somewhat popular (regular water goblets and wine glasses are still used widely).
[src:absinthe/absinthe-fountain] The absinthe glasses would commonly have a short thick stem and faceting or some other feature to indicate the correct portion to pour.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-fountain] Some were simply etched with a line or marked by a glass bead, showing how much absinthe should be poured, with another line or bead indicating the level to add water up to (the common ratio of water to absinthe is 5:1, diluting the absinthe to 11–15% ABV, close to the regular wine).
[src:absinthe/absinthe-fountain] The term 'reservoir glass' describes several styles of stemware with a distinct bulge at the bottom volumetrically equal to a standard shot or sometimes a half-shot, the remainder of the glass to be filled with water providing the correct ratio of admixture.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-fountain] They were among the first type of glass made specifically for absinthe.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-fountain] A less common variation, called the bubble-reservoir glass, contains a bubble-shaped reservoir connected to the glass by a narrow neck or portal, which allows the absinthe and water to slowly suffuse into each other, accentuating the appearance of the louche.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-fountain] A revival of absinthe began in the 1990s following the adoption of modern European Union food and beverage laws which removed long-standing barriers to its production and sale.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-fountain] As absinthe has re-emerged, so has the paraphernalia associated with it.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-fountain] Several companies produce replica absinthiana and several have modernized the traditional designs.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-fountain] Whereas absinthe barware of the 19th century was primarily used as inexpensive promotional items, the modern versions are often cast of silver, or ornately manufactured to the standard of jewelry.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-in-popular-culture] The legacy of absinthe as a mysterious, addictive, and mind-altering drink continues to this day.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-in-popular-culture] Though its psychoactive effects and chemical makeup are contested, its cultural impact is not.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-in-popular-culture] Absinthe has played a notable role in the fine art movements of Impressionism, Post-Impressionism, Surrealism, Modernism, Cubism and in the corresponding literary movements.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-in-popular-culture] The legendary drink has more recently appeared in movies, video, television, music, and contemporary literature.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-in-popular-culture] The modern absinthe revival has had a notable effect on its portrayal.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-in-popular-culture] It is often shown as an unnaturally glowing green liquid demonstrating the influence of contemporary marketing efforts.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-in-popular-culture] Absinthe has a widely documented role in 19th-century visual art and was frequently the subject of many genre paintings and still lifes of the day.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-in-popular-culture] A 1914 silent film, *Absinthe* starred King Baggot as a Parisian artist who becomes addicted to absinthe and is driven to robbery and murder.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-in-popular-culture] In the 1966 film *Madame X*, the film's star Lana Turner becomes addicted to absinthe whilst living in Mexico, one of the few countries in which absinthe was legal in the 20th century.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-in-popular-culture] A number of films such as *EuroTrip*, *Girls Trip*, *From Hell*, *Bram Stoker's Dracula* and *Moulin Rouge!* have featured hallucination sequences after characters imbibe absinthe, in reference to the drink's mythical hallucinogenic properties.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-in-popular-culture] *EuroTrip* and *Moulin Rouge!* include personifications of the "green fairy" in these sequences, played by Steve Hytner and Kylie Minogue, respectively.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-in-popular-culture] In the 2002 film *Murder by Numbers*, the film's two young antagonists (Ryan Gosling and Michael Pitt) prepare and consume absinthe while discussing the drink's notorious history.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-in-popular-culture] As prominent as absinthe's influence on visual art was, it is perhaps even more noteworthy in the context of 19th-century literature.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-in-popular-culture] Below is a short list of important authors who credited a portion of their literary success to the drink.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-in-popular-culture] Marie Corelli's *Wormwood: A Drama of Paris* (1890) was a popular novel about a Frenchman driven to murder and ruin after being introduced to absinthe.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-in-popular-culture] Corelli intended it as a morality tale on the dangers of the drink, with one contemporary scholar comparing it to the anti-drug propaganda film *Reefer Madness*.
[src:absinthe/absinthe-in-popular-culture] The book was speculated to have contributed to subsequent bans of absinthe in Europe and the United States.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Absinthe was created in the canton of Neuchâtel in Switzerland in the late 18th century by the French physician Pierre Ordinaire.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] It rose to great popularity as an alcoholic drink in late 19th- and early 20th-century France, particularly among Parisian artists and writers.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The consumption of absinthe was opposed by social conservatives and prohibitionists, partly due to its association with bohemian culture.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] From Europe and the Americas, notable absinthe drinkers included Ernest Hemingway, James Joyce, Lewis Carroll, Charles Baudelaire, Paul Verlaine, Arthur Rimbaud, and Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Absinthe has often been portrayed as a dangerously addictive psychoactive drug and hallucinogen, which gave birth to the term *absinthism*.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The chemical compound thujone, which is present in the spirit in trace amounts, was blamed for its alleged harmful effects.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] By 1915, absinthe had been banned in the United States and much of Europe, including France, the Netherlands, Belgium, Switzerland, and Austria-Hungary, though it has not been demonstrated to be any more dangerous than ordinary spirits.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Recent studies have shown that absinthe's psychoactive properties, apart from those attributable to its alcohol content, have been exaggerated.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Absinthe's revival began in the 1990s, following the adoption of modern European Union food and beverage laws that removed long-standing barriers to its production and sale.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] By the early 21st century, nearly 200 brands of absinthe were being produced in a dozen countries, most notably in France, Switzerland, Austria, Germany, the Netherlands, Spain, and the Czech Republic.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The French word *absinthe* can refer either to the alcoholic beverage, or less commonly, to the actual wormwood plant.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Absinthe is derived from the Latin *absinthium*, which in turn comes from the Greek ἀψίνθιον *apsínthion* 'wormwood'.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Some argue that the word means "undrinkable" in Greek, but it may instead be linked to the Persian root, in Persian called *spand* or *aspand* or the variant *esfand*, which meant *Peganum harmala*, also called Syrian rue in English, although it is not a variety of rue, another famously bitter herb.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] That *Artemisia absinthium* was commonly burned as a protective offering may suggest that its origins lie in the reconstructed Proto-Indo-European language root **spend*, meaning "to perform a ritual" or "make an offering".
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Whether the word was a borrowing from Persian into Greek, or from a common ancestor of both, is unclear.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Alternatively, the Greek word may originate in a pre-Greek substrate word, marked by the non-Indo-European consonant complex -νθ *-nth*.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Alternative spellings for absinthe include *absinth*, *absynthe*, and *absenta*.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] *Absinth* (without the final *e*) is a spelling variant most commonly applied to absinthes produced in central and eastern Europe, and is specifically associated with Bohemian-style absinthes.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The precise origin of absinthe is unclear.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The medical use of wormwood dates back to ancient Egypt and is mentioned in the Ebers Papyrus from around 1550 BC.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Wormwood extracts and wine-soaked wormwood leaves were used as remedies by the ancient Greeks.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Moreover, some evidence exists of a wormwood-flavoured wine in ancient Greece called *absinthites oinos*.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Lucretius' *De Rerum Natura* (I, 936–950) says that a drink containing wormwood was given as medicine to children in a cup with honey on the brim to make it drinkable.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The first evidence of absinthe, in the sense of a distilled spirit containing green anise and fennel, dates to the 18th century.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] According to popular legend, it began as an all-purpose patent remedy created by Dr.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Pierre Ordinaire, a French doctor living in Couvet, Switzerland, around 1792 (the exact date varies by account).
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Ordinaire's recipe was passed on to the Henriod sisters of Couvet, who sold it as a medicinal elixir.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] By other accounts, the Henriod sisters may have been making the elixir before Ordinaire's arrival.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] In either case, a certain Major Dubied acquired the formula from the sisters in 1797 and opened the first absinthe distillery named Dubied Père et Fils in Couvet with his son Marcellin and son-in-law Henry-Louis Pernod.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] In 1805, they built a second distillery in Pontarlier, France, under the company name Maison Pernod Fils.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Pernod Fils remained one of the most popular brands of absinthe until the drink was banned in France in 1914.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Absinthe's popularity grew steadily through the 1840s, when it was given to French troops in Algeria as a malaria preventive, and the troops brought home their taste for it.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Absinthe became so popular in bars, bistros, cafés, and cabarets by the 1860s that the hour of 5 pm was called *l'heure verte* 'the green hour'.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] It was favoured by all social classes, from the wealthy bourgeoisie to poor artists and ordinary working-class people.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] By the 1880s, mass production had caused the price to drop sharply, and the French were drinking 36 million litres (9,500,000 US gal) per year by 1910.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Absinthe was exported widely from France and Switzerland and attained some degree of popularity in other countries, including Spain, the United Kingdom, the United States, and the Czech Republic.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] It was never banned in Spain or Portugal, and its production and consumption have never ceased.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] It gained a temporary popularity spike during the early 20th century, corresponding with the Art Nouveau and Modernism aesthetic movements.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] New Orleans has a cultural association with absinthe and is credited as the birthplace of the Sazerac, perhaps the earliest absinthe cocktail.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The Old Absinthe House bar on Bourbon Street began selling absinthe in the first half of the 19th century.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Its Catalan lease-holder, Cayetano Ferrer, named it the Absinthe Room in 1874 due to the drink's popularity, which was served in the Parisian style.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] It was frequented by Mark Twain, Oscar Wilde, Franklin Delano Roosevelt, Aleister Crowley, and Frank Sinatra.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Absinthe became associated with violent crimes and social disorder, and one modern writer claims that this trend was spurred by fabricated claims and smear campaigns, which he claims were orchestrated by the temperance movement and the wine industry.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Edgar Degas's 1876 painting **The Absinthe Drinker** or **Glass of Absinthe** (**L'Absinthe**) can be seen at the Musée d'Orsay epitomising the popular view of absinthe addicts as sodden and benumbed, and Émile Zola described its effects in his novel *L'Assommoir*.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] In 1905, Swiss farmer Jean Lanfray murdered his wife and two children and then attempted to kill himself after drinking absinthe.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Lanfray had drunk a lot of wine and brandy before the killings, but that was overlooked or ignored, and blame for the murders was placed solely on his consumption of two glasses of absinthe.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The Lanfray murders were the tipping point in this hotly debated topic, and a subsequent petition collected more than 82,000 signatures to ban it in Switzerland.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] It was approved by voters, and the prohibition of absinthe was written into the Swiss constitution.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] In 1906, Belgium and Brazil banned the sale and distribution of absinthe although these were not the first countries to take such action.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] It had been banned as early as 1898 in the colony of the Congo Free State.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The Netherlands banned it in 1909, Switzerland in 1910, the United States in 1912, and France in 1914.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The prohibition of absinthe in France eventually led to the popularity of pastis, and to a lesser extent, ouzo, and other anise-flavoured spirits that do not contain wormwood.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Following the conclusion of the First World War, production of the Pernod Fils brand was resumed at the Banus distillery in Catalonia, Spain (where absinthe was still legal), but gradually declining sales saw the cessation of production in the 1960s.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] In Switzerland, the ban served only to drive the production of absinthe underground.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Clandestine home distillers produced colourless absinthe (*la Bleue*), which was easier to conceal from the authorities.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Many countries never banned absinthe, notably the United Kingdom, where it had never been as popular as in continental Europe.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] British importer BBH Spirits began to import Hill's Absinth from the Czech Republic in the 1990s, as the UK had never formally banned it, and this sparked a modern resurgence in its popularity.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] It began to reappear during a revival in the 1990s in countries where it was never banned.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Forms of absinthe available during that time consisted almost exclusively of Czech, Spanish, and Portuguese brands that were of recent origin, typically consisting of Bohemian-style products.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Connoisseurs considered these of inferior quality and not representative of the 19th-century spirit.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] In 2000, La Fée Absinthe became the first commercial absinthe distilled and bottled in France since the 1914 ban, but it is now one of dozens of brands that are produced and sold within France.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] In the Netherlands, the restrictions were challenged by Amsterdam wine seller Menno Boorsma in July 2004, thus confirming the legality of absinthe once again.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Similarly, Belgium lifted its long-standing ban on 1 January 2005 citing a conflict with the adopted food and beverage regulations of the single European Market.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] In Switzerland, the constitutional ban was repealed in 2000 during an overhaul of the national constitution although the prohibition was written into ordinary law instead.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] That law was later repealed, and absinthe was made legal on March 1, 2005.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The drink was never officially banned in Spain although it began to fall out of favour in the 1940s and almost vanished into obscurity.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Catalonia has seen a significant resurgence since 2007 when one producer established operations there.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Absinthe has never been illegal to import or manufacture in Australia although importation requires a permit under the Customs (Prohibited Imports) Regulation 1956 due to a restriction on importing any product containing oil of wormwood.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] In 2000, an amendment made all wormwood species prohibited herbs for food purposes under Food Standard 1.4.4.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Prohibited and Restricted Plants and Fungi.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] However, this amendment was found inconsistent with other parts of the pre-existing Food Code, and it was withdrawn in 2002 during the transition between the two codes, thereby continuing to allow absinthe manufacture and importation through the existing permit-based system.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] These events were erroneously reported by the media as it having been reclassified from a *prohibited* product to a *restricted* product.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] In 2007, the French brand Lucid became the first genuine absinthe to receive a Certificate of Label Approval for import into the United States since 1912, following independent efforts by representatives from Lucid and Kübler to overturn the long-standing U.S. ban.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] George Spirits of Alameda, California became the first brand of American-made absinthe produced in the United States since the ban.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Since that time, other micro-distilleries have started producing small batches in the United States.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The French Absinthe Ban of 1915 was repealed in May 2011 following petitions by the *Fédération Française des Spiritueux*, which represents French distillers, and the French Senate voted to repeal the prohibition in April 2011.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] In Switzerland, the village of Môtiers, Val-de-Travers, near Neuchâtel, became the focal point of production and promotion of the liquor after a ban of nearly 100 years was lifted.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The national *Maison de l'Absinthe* (House of Absinthe), with its attached museum, is located in the former courthouse where absinthe distillers were formerly prosecuted.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The 21st century has seen new types of absinthe, including various frozen preparations, that have become increasingly popular.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Most countries have no legal definition for absinthe, whereas the method of production and content of spirits such as whisky, brandy, and gin are globally defined and regulated.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Therefore, producers are at liberty to label a product as "absinthe" or "absinth" without regard to any specific legal definition or quality standards.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Producers of legitimate absinthes employ one of two historically defined processes to create the finished spirit – distillation or cold mixing.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] In the sole country (Switzerland) that does possess a legal definition of absinthe, distillation is the only permitted method of production.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Distilled absinthe employs a method of production similar to that of high-quality gin.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Botanicals are initially macerated in distilled base alcohol before being redistilled to exclude bitter principles, and impart the desired complexity and texture to the spirit.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The distillation of absinthe first yields a colourless distillate that leaves the alembic at around 72% ABV.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The distillate may be reduced and bottled clear, to produce a *Blanche* or *la Bleue* absinthe, or it may be coloured to create a *verte* using natural or artificial colouring.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Traditional absinthes obtain their green color strictly from the chlorophyll of whole herbs, which is extracted from the plants during the secondary maceration.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] This step involves steeping plants such as petite wormwood, hyssop, and melissa (among other herbs) in the distillate.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Chlorophyll from these herbs is extracted, giving the drink its famous green color.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] This step also provides a herbal complexity that is typical of high-quality absinthe.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The natural coloring process is critical for absinthe ageing since the chlorophyll remains chemically active.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The chlorophyll serves a similar role in absinthe as tannins do in wine or brown liquors.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] After the coloring process, the resulting product is diluted with water to the desired alcohol percentage.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The flavor of absinthe is said to improve materially with storage, and many distilleries, before the ban, aged their absinthe in settling tanks before bottling.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Many modern absinthes are produced using a cold-mix process.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] This inexpensive method of production does not involve distillation, and is regarded as inferior for the same reasons that give cause for cheaply compounded gin to be legally differentiated from distilled gin.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The cold mixing process involves the simple blending of flavouring essences and artificial colouring in commercial alcohol, in similar fashion to most flavoured vodkas and inexpensive liqueurs and cordials.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Some modern cold-mixed absinthes have been bottled at strengths approaching 90% ABV.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Others are presented simply as a bottle of plain alcohol with a small amount of powdered herbs suspended within it.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The lack of a formal legal definition in most countries to regulate the production and quality of absinthe has enabled cheaply made products to be falsely presented as traditional in production and composition.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] In Switzerland, the only country with a formal legal definition of absinthe, any absinthe product not obtained by maceration and distillation or coloured artificially cannot be sold as absinthe.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Absinthe is traditionally prepared from a distillation of neutral alcohol, various herbs, spices, and water.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Traditional absinthes were redistilled from a white grape spirit (or *eau de vie*), while lesser absinthes were more commonly made from alcohol from grains, beets, or potatoes.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The principal botanicals are grande wormwood, green anise, and florence fennel, which are often called "the holy trinity".
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Many other herbs may be used as well, such as petite wormwood (*Artemisia pontica* or Roman wormwood), hyssop, melissa, star anise, angelica, peppermint, coriander, and veronica.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] One early recipe was included in 1864's *The English and Australian Cookery Book*.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] It directed the maker to "Take of the tops of wormwood, four pounds; root of angelica, calamus aromaticus, aniseed, leaves of dittany, of each one ounce; alcohol, four gallons.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Macerate these substances during eight days, add a little water, and distil by a gentle fire, until two gallons are obtained.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Adding to absinthe's negative reputation in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, unscrupulous makers of the drink omitted the traditional colouring phase of production in favour of adding toxic copper salts to artificially induce a green tint.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] This practice may be responsible for some of the alleged toxicity historically associated with this beverage.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Many modern-day producers resort to other shortcuts, including the use of artificial food coloring to create the green color.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Additionally, at least some cheap absinthes produced before the ban were reportedly adulterated with poisonous antimony trichloride, reputed to enhance the louching effect.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Absinthe may also be naturally coloured pink or red using rose or hibiscus flowers.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] This was referred to as a *rose* (pink) or *rouge* (red) absinthe.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Only one historical brand of rose absinthe has been documented.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Absinthe was historically bottled at 45–74% ABV.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Some modern Franco–Suisse absinthes are bottled at up to 83% ABV, while some modern, cold-mixed bohemian-style absinthes are bottled at up to 89.9% ABV.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The modern-day interest in absinthe has spawned a rash of absinthe kits from sellers claiming they produce homemade absinthe.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Kits often call for soaking herbs in vodka or alcohol or adding a liquid concentrate to vodka or alcohol to create an ersatz absinthe.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Such practices usually yield a harsh substance that bears little resemblance to the genuine article and is considered inauthentic by any practical standard.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Some concoctions may even be dangerous, especially if they call for a potentially poisonous inclusion of herbs, oils, or extracts.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] In at least one documented case, a person suffered acute kidney injury after drinking 10 ml of pure wormwood oil.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] In baking and in preparing the classic New Orleans-style Sazerac cocktail, anise-flavored liqueurs and pastis have often been used as a substitute if absinthe is unavailable.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The traditional French preparation involves placing a sugar cube on top of a specially designed slotted spoon and placing the spoon on a glass filled with a measure of absinthe.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Iced water is poured or dripped over the sugar cube to mix the water into the absinthe.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The final preparation contains 1 part absinthe and 3–5 parts water.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] As water dilutes the spirit, those components with poor water solubility (mainly those from anise, fennel, and star anise) come out of solution and cloud the drink.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The resulting milky opalescence is called the *louche* (/luʃ/, French: 'opaque' or 'shady').
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The release of these dissolved essences coincides with a perfuming of herbal aromas and flavours that "blossom" or "bloom", and brings out subtleties that are otherwise muted within the neat spirit.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] This reflects what is perhaps the oldest and purest method of preparation, and is often referred to as the *French method*.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The *Bohemian method* is a recent invention that involves fire, and was not performed during absinthe's peak of popularity in the Belle Époque.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Like the French method, a sugar cube is placed on a slotted spoon over a glass containing one shot of absinthe.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The sugar is soaked in alcohol (usually more absinthe), and then set ablaze.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The flaming sugar cube is then dropped into the glass, thus igniting the absinthe.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Finally, a shot glass of water is added to douse the flames.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] This method tends to produce a stronger drink than the French method.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] A variant of the Bohemian method involves allowing the fire to extinguish on its own.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] This variant is sometimes referred to as "cooking the absinthe" or "the flaming green fairy".
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The origin of this burning ritual may borrow from a coffee and brandy drink that was served at Café Brûlot, in which a sugar cube soaked in brandy was set aflame.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Most experienced absintheurs do not recommend the Bohemian Method and consider it a modern gimmick, as it can destroy the absinthe flavour and present a fire hazard due to the unusually high alcohol content present in absinthe.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] In 19th-century Parisian cafés, upon receiving an order for absinthe, a waiter would present the patron with a dose of absinthe in a suitable glass, sugar, absinthe spoon, and a carafe of iced water.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] It was up to the patron to prepare the drink, as the inclusion or omission of sugar was strictly an individual preference, as was the amount of water used.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] As the popularity of the drink increased, additional accoutrements of preparation appeared, including the absinthe fountain, which was effectively a large jar of iced water with spigots, mounted on a lamp base.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] This lets drinkers prepare several drinks at once – and with a hands-free drip, patrons could socialise while louching a glass.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Although many bars served absinthe in standard glassware, several glasses were specifically designed for the French absinthe preparation ritual.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Absinthe glasses were typically fashioned with a dose line, bulge, or bubble in the lower portion denoting how much absinthe should be poured.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] One "dose" of absinthe ranged anywhere around 2–2.5 fluid ounces (60–75 ml).
[src:absinthe/absinthe] In addition to being prepared with sugar and water, absinthe emerged as a popular cocktail ingredient in both the United Kingdom and the United States.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] By 1930, dozens of fancy cocktails that called for absinthe had been published in numerous credible bartender guides.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] One of the most famous of these libations is Ernest Hemingway's "Death in the Afternoon" cocktail, a tongue-in-cheek concoction that contributed to a 1935 collection of celebrity recipes.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The directions are: "Pour one jigger absinthe into a Champagne glass.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Add iced Champagne until it attains the proper opalescent milkiness.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Most categorical alcoholic beverages have regulations governing their classification and labelling, while those governing absinthe have always been conspicuously lacking.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] According to popular treatises from the 19th century, absinthe could be loosely categorised into several grades (*ordinaire*, *demi-fine*, *fine*, and *Suisse* – the latter does not denote origin), in order of increasing alcoholic strength and quality.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Many contemporary absinthe critics simply classify absinthe as *distilled* or *mixed*, according to its production method.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] And while the former is generally considered far superior in quality to the latter, an absinthe's simple claim of being 'distilled' makes no guarantee as to the quality of its base ingredients or the skill of its maker.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Absinthe that is artificially coloured or clear is aesthetically stable and can be bottled in clear glass.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] If naturally colored absinthe is exposed to light or air for a prolonged period, the chlorophyll gradually becomes oxidized, which has the effect of gradually changing the color from green to yellow green, and eventually to brown.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The colour of absinthe that has completed this transition was historically referred to as *feuille morte* ("dead leaf").
[src:absinthe/absinthe] In the pre-ban era, this natural phenomenon was favourably viewed, for it confirmed the product in question was coloured naturally, and not artificially with potentially toxic chemicals.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Predictably, vintage absinthes often emerge from sealed bottles as distinctly amber in tint due to decades of slow oxidation.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Though this colour change presents no adverse impact to the flavour of absinthe, it is generally desired to preserve the original colour, which requires that naturally coloured absinthe be bottled in dark, light-resistant bottles.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Absinthe intended for decades of storage should be kept in a cool (room temperature), dry place, away from light and heat.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Absinthe should not be stored in the refrigerator or freezer, as the anethole may polymerise inside the bottle, creating an irreversible precipitate, and adversely impacting the original flavour.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Absinthe has been frequently described in modern times as being hallucinogenic, a claim refuted by modern science.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The belief that absinthe induces hallucinogenic effects is rooted, at least partly, in the findings of 19th-century French psychiatrist Valentin Magnan, who carried out ten years of experiments with wormwood oil.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] In the course of this research, he studied 250 cases of alcoholism and concluded that those who abused absinthe were worse off than those who abused other alcoholic drinks, experiencing rapid-onset hallucinations.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Such accounts by opponents of absinthe (like Magnan) were cheerfully embraced by famous absinthe drinkers, many of whom were bohemian artists or writers.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Two famous artists who helped popularise the notion that absinthe had powerful psychoactive properties were Toulouse-Lautrec and Vincent van Gogh.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] In one of the best-known written accounts of absinthe drinking, an inebriated Oscar Wilde described a phantom sensation of having tulips brush against his legs after leaving a bar at closing time.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Notions of absinthe's alleged hallucinogenic properties were again fuelled in the 1970s when a scientific paper suggested that thujone's structural similarity to tetrahydrocannabinol (THC), the active chemical in cannabis, presented the possibility of THC receptor affinity.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Counterevidence to this was published in 1999.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The debate over whether absinthe produces effects on the human mind in addition to those of alcohol has not been resolved conclusively.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The effects of absinthe have been described by some as mind-opening.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The most commonly reported experience is a "clear-headed" feeling of inebriation – a form of "lucid drunkenness".
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Chemist, historian, and absinthe distiller Ted Breaux has claimed that the alleged secondary effects of absinthe may be because some of the herbal compounds in the drink act as stimulants, while others act as sedatives, creating an overall lucid effect of awakening.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The long-term effects of moderate absinthe consumption in humans remain unknown, although herbs traditionally used to produce absinthe are reported to have both painkilling and antiparasitic properties.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Today it is known that absinthe does not cause hallucinations.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] It was once widely promoted that excessive absinthe drinking caused effects that were discernible from those associated with alcoholism, a belief that led to the coining of the term *absinthism*.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] One of the first vilifications of absinthe followed an 1864 experiment in which Magnan simultaneously exposed one guinea pig to large doses of pure wormwood vapour, and another to alcohol vapours.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The guinea pig exposed to wormwood vapour experienced convulsive seizures, while the animal exposed to alcohol did not.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Magnan would later blame the naturally occurring (in wormwood) chemical thujone for these effects.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Thujone, once widely believed to be an active chemical in absinthe, is a GABA antagonist, and while it can produce muscle spasms in large doses, there is no direct evidence to suggest it causes hallucinations.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Past reports estimated thujone concentrations in absinthe as being up to 260 mg/kg.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] As such, most traditionally crafted absinthes, both vintage and modern, fall within the current EU standards.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Tests conducted on mice to study toxicity showed an oral LD50 of about 45 mg thujone per kg of body weight, which represents far more absinthe than could be realistically consumed.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The high percentage of alcohol in absinthe would result in mortality long before thujone could become a factor.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] In documented cases of acute thujone poisoning as a result of oral ingestion, the source of thujone was not commercial absinthe, but rather non-absinthe-related sources, such as common essential oils (which may contain as much as 50% thujone).
[src:absinthe/absinthe] One study published in the *Journal of Studies on Alcohol* concluded that high doses (0.28 mg/kg) of thujone in alcohol had negative effects on attention performance in a clinical setting.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] It delayed reaction time, and caused subjects to concentrate their attention on the central field of vision.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Low doses (0.028 mg/kg) did not produce an effect noticeably different from the plain alcohol control.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] While the effects of the high dose samples were statistically significant in a double blind test, the test subjects themselves were unable to reliably identify which samples contained thujone.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] For the average 65 kg (143 lb) man, the high dose samples in the study would equate to 18.2 mg of thujone.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The EU limit of 35 mg/L of thujone in absinthe means that given the highest permitted thujone content, that individual would need to consume approximately 0.5 litres of high-proof (e.g.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] 50%+ ABV) spirit before the thujone could be metabolized to display effects detectable in a clinical setting, which would result in a potentially lethal BAC of >0.4%.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Most countries (except Switzerland) at present do not possess a legal definition of absinthe (unlike Scotch whisky or cognac).
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Accordingly, producers are free to label a product "absinthe" or "absinth", whether or not it bears any resemblance to the traditional spirit.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Absinthe is readily available in many bottle shops.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Bitters may contain a maximum 35 mg/kg thujone, while other alcoholic beverages can contain a maximum 10 mg/kg.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The domestic production and sale of absinthe is regulated by state licensing laws.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] These controls have now been repealed, and permission is no longer required.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Absinthe was prohibited in Brazil until 1999 and was brought by entrepreneur Lalo Zanini and legalised in the same year.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Presently, absinthe sold in Brazil must abide by the national law that restricts all spirits to a maximum of 54% ABV.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] While this regulation is enforced throughout channels of legal distribution, it may be possible to find absinthe containing alcohol in excess of the legal limit in some restaurants or food fairs.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] In Canada, liquor laws concerning the production, distribution, and sale of spirits are written and enforced by individual provincial government monopolies.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Each product is subject to the approval of a respective individual provincial liquor board before it can be sold in that province.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Importation is a federal matter and is enforced by the Canada Border Services Agency.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The importation of a nominal amount of liquor by individuals for personal use is permitted, provided that conditions for the individual's duration of stay outside the country are satisfied.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] In 2007, Canada's first genuine absinthe (Taboo Absinthe) was created by Okanagan Spirits Craft Distillery in British Columbia.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The European Union permits a maximum thujone level of 35 mg/kg in alcoholic beverages where *Artemisia* species is a listed ingredient, and 10 mg/kg in other alcoholic beverages.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Member countries regulate absinthe production within this framework.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The sale of absinthe is permitted in all EU countries unless they further regulate it.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The sale and production of absinthe was prohibited in Finland from 1919 to 1932; no current prohibitions exist.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The government-owned chain of liquor stores (Alko) is the only outlet that may sell alcoholic beverages containing over 8% ABV, although national law bans the sale of alcoholic beverages containing over 80% ABV.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Édouard Manet's first major painting *The Absinthe Drinker* was controversial, and was rejected by the Paris Salon in 1859.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] French producers circumvented this regulatory obstacle by labelling absinthe as *spiritueux à base de plantes d'absinthe* ('wormwood-based spirits'), with many either reducing or omitting fennel and hyssop altogether from their products.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] A legal challenge to the scientific basis of this decree resulted in its repeal (2009), which opened the door for the official French re-legalisation of absinthe for the first time since 1915.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The French Senate voted to repeal the prohibition in mid-April 2011.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] A ban on absinthe was enacted in Germany on 27 March 1923.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] In addition to banning the production of commercial trade in absinthe, the law went so far as to prohibit the distribution of printed matter that provided details of its production.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The original ban was lifted in 1981, but the use of *Artemisia absinthium* as a flavouring agent remained prohibited.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] On 27 September 1991, Germany adopted the European Community's standards of 1988, which effectively re-legalised absinthe.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The Fascist regime in 1926 banned the production, import, transport, and sale of any liquor named *Assenzio*.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The ban was reinforced in 1931 with harsher penalties for transgressors and remained in force until 1992 when the Italian government amended its laws to comply with the EU directive 88/388/EEC.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Although absinthe is not prohibited at the national level, some local authorities have banned it.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The ban came in August 2008 after several issues of misuse drew public and police attention.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] One incident resulted in breathing difficulties and hospitalising of a 17-year-old for alcohol poisoning.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The particular brand of absinthe that caused these effects was bottled at 89% ABV.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The sale and production of absinthe has never been prohibited in Sweden or Norway.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] However, the only outlet that may sell alcoholic beverages containing more than 3.5% ABV in Sweden and 4.75% ABV in Norway is the government-owned chain of liquor stores known as Systembolaget in Sweden and Vinmonopolet in Norway.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Systembolaget and Vinmonopolet did not import or sell absinthe for many years after the ban in France; however, today several absinthes are available for purchase in Systembolaget stores, including Swedish made distilled absinthe.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] In Norway, on the other hand, one is less likely to find many absinthes since Norwegian alcohol law prohibits the sale and importation of alcoholic beverages above 60% ABV, which eliminates most absinthes.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] In Switzerland, the sale and production of absinthe was prohibited from 1910 to 1 March 2005.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] This was based on a vote in 1908, inspired by the Jean Lanfray incident.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] To be legally made or sold in Switzerland, absinthe must be distilled, must not contain certain additives, and must be either naturally coloured or left uncoloured.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] In 2014, the Federal Administrative Court of Switzerland invalidated a governmental decision of 2010 which allowed only absinthe made in the Val-de-Travers region to be labelled as absinthe in Switzerland.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The court found that absinthe was a label for a product and was not tied to a geographic origin.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Absinthe was never legally prohibited in the UK, but was not imported for a 70-year period.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] In 2007, the Alcohol and Tobacco Tax and Trade Bureau (TTB) effectively lifted the long-standing absinthe ban, and it has since approved many brands for sale in the US market.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] This was made possible partly through the TTB's clarification of the Food and Drug Administration's (FDA) thujone content regulations, which specify that finished food and beverages that contain *Artemisia* species must be thujone-free.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] In this context, the TTB considers a product thujone-free if the thujone content is less than 10 ppm (equal to 10 mg/kg).
[src:absinthe/absinthe] This is verified through the use of gas chromatography–mass spectrometry.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The brands Kübler and Lucid and their lawyers did most of the work to get absinthe legalized in the U.S., over the 2004–2007 time period.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] In the U.S., 5 March sometimes is referred to as "National Absinthe Day", as it was the day the 95-year ban on absinthe was finally lifted.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Absinthe imported in violation of these regulations is subject to seizure at the discretion of U.S.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Numerous artists and writers living in France in the late 19th and early 20th centuries were noted absinthe drinkers and featured absinthe in their work.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Some of these included Édouard Manet, Guy de Maupassant, Paul Verlaine, Amedeo Modigliani, Edgar Degas, Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec, Vincent van Gogh, Oscar Wilde, Arthur Rimbaud, and Émile Zola.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Many other renowned artists and writers similarly drew from this cultural well, including Aleister Crowley, Ernest Hemingway, Pablo Picasso, August Strindberg, and Erik Satie.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] The aura of illicitness and mystery surrounding absinthe has played into literature, movies, music, and television, where it is often portrayed as a mysterious, addictive, and mind-altering drink.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Intended as a morality tale on the dangers of the drink, it was speculated to have contributed to subsequent bans of absinthe in Europe and the United States.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] Some of the earliest film references include *The Hasher's Delirium* (1910) by Émile Cohl, an early pioneer in the art of animation, as well as two different silent films, each titled *Absinthe*, from 1913 and 1914 respectively.
[src:absinthe/absinthe] More recently, it served as the title of a 2018 song by the indie group I Don't Know How But They Found Me.
[src:absinthe/acadian-cuisine] Acadian cuisine is not very well known in Canada or internationally.
[src:absinthe/acadian-cuisine] It has much in common with Québécois cuisine because of its geographical proximity.
[src:absinthe/acadian-cuisine] The two often feature the same dishes, but the cuisine of Acadia puts more emphasis on seafood.
[src:absinthe/acadian-cuisine] Acadian cuisine has notably served as the base for Cajun cuisine because the Cajun are descendants of Acadians who were deported to Louisiana.Note 2 It is also believed that Acadians are responsible for normalizing potato consumption in France—a vegetable the French once considered poisonous.
[src:absinthe/acadian-cuisine] In the 17th century, French colonists who settled on lands they named Acadia adapted their 16th-century French cuisine to incorporate the crops, seafood and animals that flourished in the region.
[src:absinthe/acadian-cuisine] Their descendants became the Acadian people and their ingenuity created Acadian cuisine.
[src:absinthe/acadian-cuisine] After the English conquered Acadia during the 18th century, they decided to deport the Acadians and take their settlements, which were often built on the most fertile earth in the colony.
[src:absinthe/acadian-cuisine] Most Acadians did not manage to escape the deportation.
[src:absinthe/acadian-cuisine] But, of those who did, most fled to the east and north of New BrunswickNote 3.
[src:absinthe/acadian-cuisine] As such, Acadian cuisine in the 18th century was refocused around what could be grown, hunted and fished in the less fertile lands of the East Coast of New Brunswick and the Upper St.
[src:absinthe/acadian-cuisine] Acadian cuisine often features fish and seafood, especially cod and Atlantic herring, but also mackerel, berlicoco, lobster, crab, salmon, mussels, trout, clams, flounder, smelt and scallops.
[src:absinthe/acadian-cuisine] Most fish is consumed fresh, but some are *boucané* (smoked), marinated or salted.
[src:absinthe/acadian-cuisine] The most commonly used meat is pork, followed by chicken and beef.
[src:absinthe/acadian-cuisine] As with the rest of North America, turkey is commonly consumed during the holidays.
[src:absinthe/acadian-cuisine] Game like deer, hare, ruffed grouse and moose is consumed regularly in some regions.
[src:absinthe/acadian-cuisine] Game will replace livestock meat if present and can be given as a gift.
[src:absinthe/acadian-cuisine] In some regions, for example Caraquet and the Îles-de-la-Madeleine, more unusual game is or was caught, like seal, bear and seagull.
[src:absinthe/acadian-cuisine] The vegetables of Acadian cuisine are the potato, onion, carrot, turnip, legume, beet, squash and corn.
[src:absinthe/acadian-cuisine] These vegetables were popular because they were easily preserved for the winter in root cellars and jars.
[src:absinthe/acadian-cuisine] The fiddlehead fern was introduced to the Acadians by the indigenous Maliseet, Mi'kmaq and Penobscot peoples in the early 18th Century and remains a popular Acadian dish.
[src:absinthe/acadian-cuisine] Popular fruits include blueberries, apples, strawberries, raspberries, blackberries, plums, pears and cranberries.
[src:absinthe/acadian-cuisine] Some ingredients like rice, molasses, dried raisins and brown sugar are part of Acadian cuisine because of historical commerce between Acadia and regions like the Antilles and Brazil.
[src:absinthe/acadian-cuisine] Maple sugar is also a popular sweetener, given the often-close familial ties between Quebec (the world's largest producer of maple sugar) and Acadia.
